      p.
        <span style="text-transform:uppercase;font-weight:700">Background:</span><br>
        Drapermeter is a web application that lets participants rate advertisements based on their creativity. This project is done
        as part of my Masters Thesis at the University of Florida. Drapermeter verifies an existing theory in Advertising Creativity known
        as the <a href="">Creative Product Semantic Scale (CPSS)</a>. According to CPSS, any product or service can be deemed creative if it scores highly
        on the following three scales : <br>
        1. Novelty <br>
        2. Elaboration <br>
        3. Style <br>
        To understand the effects of creativity on the effectiveness of advertisement and the differences between judgement of creativity by regular consumers and creative professionals is
        studied through an online survey tool that asks participants to rate award winning advertisements based on the above three scales. These results are then
        undergone some statistical analysis to see if there is a correlation between the above scales and the overall creativity of an advertisement.<br><br>
        <span style="text-transform:uppercase;font-weight:700">Research:</span><br>
        Surveys that provide good user experience are proven to obtain better quality of data than typical surveys that fail to engage participants. To better understand
        the current trends in survey design, three popular survey applications are studied. Following are the major differences between each:
      img(style="width:100%",src="/assets/img/hp_gallery_tn/comparison.png")
      p.
        This survey will have 27 questions in total with 9 questions for each advertisement. Building a survey of 27 questions using any of the above three apps results
        in a long vertical navigation or 27 repeated clicks. Moreover, our requirement is that the user should see the advertisement before answering a question and none of the above
        mentioned survey platforms provide this feature. Therefore, I decided to build a custom survey application for this research that fits the needs and almost gamifies the survey experience.<br><br>
        <span style="text-transform:uppercase;font-weight:700">UX Design process:</span><br>
        Based on the research paper <a href= "http://dl.acm.org/citation.cfm?id=2639230">"Gamification of online surveys: conceptual foundations and a design process based on the MDA framework"</a>, following
        5 steps are devised for the development of an interactive survey:<br>
        1. Inspiration<br>
        2. Aesthetics and Relationships<br>
        3. Dynamics and Conversations<br>
        4.  Mechanics and Appearance<br>
        5. Prototyping, Evaluation and Iteration<br>
        <span style="font-weight:700">1. Inspiration:</span><br>
        At this stage, existing work in survey design that deviates from the mainstream in terms of UI elements and the overall user experience are studied. Here are some of them:<br>
        <a href="http://slaveryfootprint.org/">Made in a free world: Slavery Footprint Survey</a><br>
        <a href="http://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2013/12/20/sunday-review/dialect-quiz-map.html">New York Times: How Yâ€™all, Youse and You Guys Talk</a><br>
        <a href="http://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2011/06/19/nyregion/how-many-households-are-like-yours.html">New York Times: How Many Households Are Like Yours?</a><br>
        In my observations, following elements align with the concepts discussed in the research that are providing a compelling survey experience:<br>
        - Providing visual feedback for an input<br>
        - Using subtle animations during transitions<br>
        - Informing the participant about background of the survey<br>
        - Usage of sliders and other interactive elements for data input<br>
